In the indels dir, I was observing that minimap2 alignments werent great for detecting indels that coorespond to TEs
I read that a wavefront aligner might help solve, but alas, my alignments are crappy (you can see by the gap compressed sequence identity in column 4). Im seeing 70% sequence idenity between syntenic segments of two arabidosis genomes, which doesnt seem right.  
Not entirely sure the issue. I think enforcing global end-to-end alignments over large swaths (>1mb) causes forced errors over structurally variable regions, but not sure. 
Its built with 'synmap_split.py' in mind, which uses JCVI anchors and minimap2. 
My anchor approach uses blocks of genes. I may be able to solve the issue by shortening to syntenic pairs:
> genome1
[gene1_start].......[gene2_end]
> genome2
[gene1_start].......[gene2_end]

Rather than:
> genome1
[block1_start].......[block1_end]
> genome2
[block1_start].......[block1_end]


I address the above probelm a little:
# This version does gene-to-gene rather than block-to-block.
python window_identity/bin/gene_coords_extractor_all4_pairs.py -mcscan Col0.Alt5.clean.anchors  > Col0.Alt5.clean.anchors.mod.coords.pairs
# Remove redundancies.
python window_identity/bin/anchor_coord_subtracter.py Col0.Alt5.clean.anchors.mod.coords.pairs Col0.Alt5.clean.anchors.mod.coords.pairs.clean
# Here, I need '-d' to signify to keep those alignment sequences so I can use them with wavefront. 
python window_identity/bin/synmap_split.py -c Col0.Alt5.clean.anchors.mod.coords.pairs.clean -d --preset asm5 -t 20 -p 200

# I can use something like this to run wavefront over each temp file.
#!/usr/bin/env bash
set -euo pipefail

# Directory containing your syntenic-pair subdirs
MINIMAP_DIR="./minimap_temp"

# Path to the wavefront_global binary
WAVE_BIN="./window_identity/dev/wavefront/wavefront_global"

# Output file (will be created/truncated)
OUTFILE="wavefront_alns.tsv"
: > "$OUTFILE"

export WAVE_BIN OUTFILE

# Find each subdirectory under MINIMAP_DIR, then for each one:
#   - run wavefront_global on the Alt5*.fa and Col0*.fa files
#   - append output to $OUTFILE
# Up to 10 jobs will run in parallel.
find "$MINIMAP_DIR" -mindepth 1 -maxdepth 1 -type d | \
  xargs -P1 -I {} bash -c ' ##### I CAN CRANK UP P HERE FOR MULTITHREADING, BUT MULT-CORES PUSHING TO "$OUTFILE" AT THE SAME TIME CAUSES LINES TO SPLIT AND NEST. WOULD NEED TO FIX. '-P1' WORKS.
    "$WAVE_BIN" "$1"/Alt5*.fa "$1"/Col0*.fa >> "$OUTFILE"
  ' _ {}

echo "Done — all alignments are in $OUTFILE"


